{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6303e380-ecb0-4f3f-a213-4e33c250cd21","content":"```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis uses the `~` (contains) operator to match any test whose fully qualified name includes `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds` while skipping the `EmailNotificationTests`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d04a5e50-bd24-46e1-a8d0-74bd0629c311","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses its own test adapter. To filter by class name with `dotnet test`, you use the `--filter` option.\n\nFor TUnit, the filter syntax uses `FullyQualifiedName` or `ClassName`. The standard dotnet test filter for class name would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nor using fully qualified name contains:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThe `~` operator means \"contains\". This should work for TUnit since it integrates with the dotnet test infrastructure.","outputTokens":255,"requestId":"982B:1B0168:10D1FDA:150530F:69FFDF30"},"id":"eafafc13-f691-4f4a-99a3-eac7155cf479","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:28:23.881Z","parentId":"db99658c-914e-4f39-b632-a28be85666b3"}
